accessible to all, directly playable through a streaming application and you have the option of making it private... <br/>Same for documents, and office appliances, which could simply have been connected to existing internet based applications... <br/>Technically when you upload, you upload to the cloud anyway, so this might simply have been a "strategical" choice, in order to be as close as possible to existing operating systems, to make the transition easier for the majority, and/or promote the use of proprietary appliances. <br/>It would have been nice to see operating systems that directly connect to the cloud, but then we can build applications on top of them, so why not:<br /><ul style="margin-bottom: -40px"><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">Build a cloud uploader, just as described above</li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">...Use proximity datacenters for load/traffic/distribution optimization(a google  branded system?)</li><br /></ul><br /></li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">Related to the above: distributions... will be nice to see how this is handled, because it certainly going to be a major \'success\' factor...</li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">None of these two operating systems is Open Source (one\'s commercial intent is pretty clear, behind the slogans). Which means that if we for example wanted to use the same xml communication logic, we would have to write our own, which actually means doing the same thing 3 times...<br/>But hey...</li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">And about xml application communication interface, should that be the same in the sibos (search internet based operating system), or should it go all the way implementing search based communication interface also? Well it should be a mixture of the both, where generic commands would trigger the usage of specific, structured commands. For example : <span style="border:1px solid #CFCFCF;">ask for login</span> generic command would trigger the usage of the <span style="border:1px solid #CFCFCF;">display login screen</span> structured command</li><br /></ul><br /><br />All of this being said, it now seems even more actual to start building a foss (free & open source software) isbos / sibos...", "updated": "2009-04-26T02:09:43.591-07:00", "title": "Search Based Operating System (2): Internet Based Operating System", "comments": [], "blog": "4979118888770430827", "tag": "blogger.com", "year": "1999", "id": "7206289283476661869", "categories": "machine,development,interface,human'}, {"content": "<span style="font-weight:bold;">Idea </span><br />The principle is that our operating systems are now "ready made", coming with specific applications, shortcuts to access these applications, interfaces ... All of this for the sake of simplicity, to better work for us... <br />These systems have solidly been proven, but perhaps it is time for more open, "intelligent", flexible, integrated into the "network" systems to take over... <br /><br />So ... <br /><br />The idea is that the operating system would arrive "naked", with nothing but a search interface ... The principle being that the user enriches "his" operating system through his interactions with it... An example of interaction: <br /><ul type="square" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -20px"><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">the user (you): Performs the search <span style="border:1px solid #CFCFCF;">open my emails</span><br /></li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">System: ...presents a list of email clients, web, desktop, or other ... (gmail, outlook, hotmail ...), with the possibility of filtering according to different criteria (free, open source, web / desktop ...)<br /></li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">User selects an application, gmail for example :-)</li><br /><ul style="margin-top: -15px; margin-bottom: -20px"><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">the system offers the option to link this application to the request ("do you want to use <i>gmail</i> for <span style="border: 1px solid #CFCFCF">open my emails</span>?")</li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">... and according to the data and the constraints of the application, creates, obtains, installs, or composes the corresponding interface ... It would here be a login interface (user, password)</li><br /></ul><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">User logs in</li><br /><li style="margin-top:-15px">the system sends data, receives a response, and presents it to the user (list of emails ...)</li><br /></ul><br /><br />... the interaction continues, and the system stores data along the way so as to respond instantly to the user the next times ... <br /><br />"Everything" would happen through the search interface, as the system would consider itself as being an application, just like any other... System configuration for example: <br /><ul type="square" style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: -20px"><br /><li style="margin-top: -15px">user: <span style="border: 1px solid #CFCFCF">change system configuration: emails</span></li><br /><li style="margin-top: -15px">the system would first search for the corresponding interfaces "internally", and every where else... The first instance it should return should be the one corresponding to the configuration of the previous query, for example ...</li><br /></ul><br />Other configuration / administration queries could be: <span style="border: 1px solid #CFCFCF">create user</span>, <span style="border: 1px solid #CFCFCF">change language</span>, <span style="border: 1px solid #CFCFCF">view history</span> ... <br /><br />The system would work just like a search engine, so the applications would be sought / classified according to similar criteria (number of users / uses, categories, name, textual search in description ...). <br /><br />And the user would be able to "teach" the system the "meaning" of a query when it unduly does not return results (combining queries and filters that return the wanted results, for example) ... This feature would be purely experimental, because being part of the "whole discipline" mentioned below ... <br /><br />As for the intelligence of the system itself, in the <span style="border: 1px solid #CFCFCF">open my emails</span>, the system should ideally be able to understand the "my"... but then, this is a project, actually a whole discipline in itself ... <br /><br />A system like this would fully take advantage of the power of the web paradigm (knowledge web, information web, data web...), and would completely be open to evolution as "everything" would be subject to change, including its basic mechanisms ... <br /><br />In fact, the only limit of this system would on one hand and apparently be the state of artificial intelligence technology, on the other and in reality, the Imagination of its users ...<br /><br /><span style="font-weight:bold;">Project Development</span><br />Project hosted <a href="http://code.google.com/p/sibos/">here</a>.<br />Participations would warmly be welcomed...<br /><br /><span style="font-weight:bold;">Idea : raw design </span>(<a href="http://www.molhokwai.net-a.googlepages.com/component_design_0.jpg" target="_blank" style="font-size: xx-small;">click here if you do not see the image...</a>)<br /><a href="http://www.molhokwai.net-a.googlepages.com/component_design_0.jpg" target="_blank"><image src="http://www.molhokwai.net-a.googlepages.com/component_design_0.jpg" style="width:400px; height:260px; cursor:pointer;" title="click to see full size" alt="click to see image..."/></a>", "updated": "2009-03-14T07:36:45.523-07:00", "title": "Search Based Operating System", "comments": [], "blog": "4979118888770430827", "tag": "blogger.com", "year": "1999", "id": "4963005638433911031", "categories": "machine,development,interface,human'}, {"content": "<span style="font-weight:bold;">Idea</span><br />In the same spirit of free production, a free choreography, a choreography that would be created, produced and presented freely ...<br /><br />Here there would not be any p